DO  -  10.1016/j.maturitas.2023.04.219
AB  -  Context: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is one of the most common endocrine and metabolic disorders among women of reproductive age. Evidence suggests that overweight or obese women with PCOS may be at higher risk of cardiovascular diseases (CVDs). Objective: To access the effect of orlistat combined with drospirenone/ethinylestradiol tablets (DRSP/EE) on the cardiovascular risk factors compared to DRSP/EE‐alone in overweight or obese patients with PCOS. Methods: We conducted a randomized controlled trial involving 76 overweight or obese PCOS patients [body mass index (BMI) ≥24 kg/m2]. All participants were randomly assigned into two groups in a 1:2 ratio to receive DRSP/EE alone as the control group(n=25) or DRSP/EE plus Orlistat as the observation group(n=51) for 12 weeks. Both groups got the same comprehensive intervention regarding diet and physical activities, which is standardized in our hospital. Changes in cardiovascular risk factors including Lipoprotein(a)[Lp(a)], fasting plasma glucose (FPG), uric acid (UA), triglycerides (TG), cholesterol (TC), low density lipoprotein‐cholesterol (LDL‐C), high density lipoprotein‐cholesterol (HDL‐C), serum calcium‐phosphorus product (CaxP) and homocysteine (HCY) were observed before and after different regiments. Result(s): After 12 weeks of treatment, Lp(a), FPG, UA, TC, LDL‐C and HCY in both two groups decreased compared to the baseline, while the levels of HDL‐C and TG increased. However, Lp(a), FPG, UA, TC and LDL‐C decreased significantly in the observation group (P<0.05). There was no significant difference in (CaxP) and HCY between the two groups after treatment (P>0.05). Conclusion(s): Orlistat combined with DRSP/EE might have beneficial effects on the decrease of the risk of cardiovascular disease for overweight or obese PCOS patients, which provides evidence for the choice of rational drug use in clinical practice. *Corresponding author: Professor Xiangyan Ruan, E‐Mail: ruanxiangyan@ccmu.edu.cn Funding: This work was supported by Beijing Municipal Administration of Hospitals' Ascent Plan (No. DFL20181401).
