DO  -  10.1093/ndt/gfv193.11
AB  -  Introduction and Aims: When concerning phosphate binders, sevelamer has an unique effect as a resine that can act as a prebiothic. Avoiding calcium intake and through pleiotropic effects, there might be a differential influence of phosphate binders (PB) as sevelamer and calcium based PB in terms of cardiovascular risk profile. The aim of this study was to evaluate the effects of phosphorus binders on serum uric acid, HbA1c and lipid profile levels and the progression of arterial stiffness. Methods: A total of 151 patients (mean age: 53.0 ± 14.4 years; mean duration of dialysis: 9.5 ± 1.2 years) undergoing maintenance hemodialysis and using the same phosphorus binders under three years follow‐up were enrolled into the study. Patients were divided into two groups according to usage of phosphate binders (PB) as sevelamer based PB (group 1; n: 99) and calcium based PB (group 2; n.52 ). Biochemical parameters as fasting plasma glucose (FPG), hemoglobin A1c (HbA1c), calcium, phosphorus, bicarbonate, C‐reactive protein (CRP), lipid prophile (total cholesterol [C], HDL‐C, TGs, LDL‐C [low‐density lipoprotein C; computed from Friedewald's formula]), uric acid and urea reduction rate (URR) were assessed from monthly clinical visits in three year follow up period. Arterial stiffness determined at the initial and at the end of the 3rd year by aortic pulse wave velocity (PWV) (Sphygmo‐Cor). Results: Serum calcium, phosphorus, parathyroid hormone, CRP and URR levels were similar in two groups. Serum LDL‐C levels and PWv values were significantly lower in group 1 (p<0.005). When compared to initial results; mean üric acid levels had significantly decreased in group 1 where remained stable in group 2 in three years follow up period (group 1: ‐1.4 ± 0.1 mg/dl vs group 2: 0.1 ± 0.2 mg/dl p:0.000). 22.4% of patients in group 1 and 3.8% of patients in group 2 showed a reduction more than 2 mg/ dl in mean üric acid levels. Fasting plasma glucose ( p:0.001) and HbA1c (p<0.005) levels were significantly lower in diabetic group 1 patients than group 2. PWv values were similar in both groups at the inital of the study. However; PWv values of group 1 patients were significantly lower than group 2 at the 3rd year of the study (p<0.005) Conclusions: Despite similar phosphorus levels and dialysis adequency, sevelamer improves the cardiovascular risk by pleiotropic effects through lowing uric acid, LDL‐C and HbA1c concentrations and avoiding the excess calcium intake Thus, sevelamer improves the cardiovascular risk profile of hemodialysis patients and prevents the progression of arterial stiffness when compared to calcium based phosphate binders.
