AB  -  Background: Anti‐angiogenic TKI is the most potential effective strategy for patients (pts) with progressive radioiodine refractory differentiated thyroid cancer (RAIR‐DTC). This phase II trial assessed apatinib, an oral TKI against VEGFR‐2, in RAIR‐DTC. Methods: Twenty pts were sequentially recruited to receive apatinib with two dosing schedules, 750 or 500 mg qd initially. Interruption and dose reduction to 500 and 250 mg qd were allowed. Results: Baseline data are shown in the Table. Data cut‐off date was 12/15/2017. The median time for thyroglobulin (Tg) decline of ≥ 30% was 3.3 wks (750 mg: 4.0; 500 mg: 2.4). The best objective response rate was as high as 80% (750 mg: 90%; 500 mg: 70%), and the disease control rate reached 100%. Pts achieved the first partial response after 8.1 wks (750 mg: 8.1; 500 mg: 8.0). The median progression‐free survival was 16.6 (95%CI, 7.4‐18.5) mos (750 mg: 17.6; 500 mg: 13.8). The median overall survival had not reached. All pts had drug‐related adverse events (DRAEs). Grade ≥3 DRAEs were reported in 17 (85%) pts: 10 (100%) and 7 (70%) pts in 750 and 500 mg schedule, causing a dose reduction of 100% pts receiving 750 mg schedule, but of 50% pts receiving 500 mg schedule, respectively. The most common Grade ≥3 DRAEs in pts with 750 mg schedule included hypertension, hand‐foot‐skin reaction (HFSR), hypocalcemia, diarrhea, stomach pain and anal mucositis, while those in pts with 500 mg schedule were hypertension and HFSR. The incidence of DRAEs of any grade and Grade ≥3 DRAEs within the first 8 wks following apatinib were comparable with those thereafter, as well as the safety profile. Conclusions: Apatinib represents a new treatment option for progressive RAIR‐DTC with rapid response, good efficacy and acceptable tolerance.
