AB  -  Fifty‐six inpatients undergoing total hip replacement were included in an intensive 70‐day preoperative and immediately postoperative rehabilitation program. Additionally, they were treated with injections of placebo (PL‐I) (n = 23; mean age, 62 ± 2 years) or salmon calcitonin (CT‐I) (n = 23; mean age, 63 ± 1 years) on a double‐blind basis or with salmon calcitonin spray (CT‐S) (n = 10; mean age, 59 ± 3 years). Calcitonin decreased pain, especially if severe. Laboratory and immunological parameters were monitored at five and three intervals during the study, respectively. Major differences were found between the PL‐I, CT‐I, and CT‐S groups in acid and alkaline phosphatase, serum calcium and phosphate, urinary hydroxyproline and urine volume, and transferrin and immunoglobulin (Ig). Major differences were even seen between the CT‐I and CT‐S groups in calcium and phosphate levels, acid and alkaline phosphatase, and urinary hydroxyproline and urine volume. All three groups differed in their acute‐phase response. No major differences were found in blood glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, IgG, IgM, orosomucoid, ceruloplasmin, alpha2‐macroglobulin, prealbumin, or C3 complement. Calcitonin administration, in addition to the intensive rehabilitation program, reduced morbidity after total hip replacement, induced a number of beneficial metabolic responses, and reduced pain.
