AB  -  Introduction: Few cases of In‐Vitro Fertilization–induced Hypertriglyceridemia with secondary Acute Pancreatitis have been reported. This is a serious and life‐threatening complication. In high‐risk patients (diabetes, PCOS, obesity, dyslipidemia[DLP] family/personal history) DLP screening before initiating IVF and subsequent monitoring are mandatory. Case Description: Age 28: Primary Infertility, PCOS Age 30: HTG ( >1000), Hypercholesterolemia; Rx Statin+Fibrate. No family history of DLP, IHD or AP Age 33 [2020 Aug]: IVF Cycle 1 [Estradiol 2 mg tid; Prednisolone 10 mg bid; Dydrogesterone 10 mg x 1 month]. Hospitalised for pain abdomen and vomiting; IV Fluids; ? AP [not documented]; ?? Ovarian hyperstimulation Age 33 [2020 Dec]: IVF Cycle 2 [Estradiol 2 mg tid; Prednisolone 10 mg bid; Dydrogesterone 10 mg x 1 month] 10 Dec: Statin+Fibrate stopped. Embryo Transfer done; failed 28 Dec: Hospitalised for severe acute epigastric pain, vomiting, ileus; S amylase 220 U/L; CT Abdomen: Acute pancreatitis; S Triglycerides: 1707 mg/dl. Statin restarted 2021 Jan 10: S Amylase 225 [U/L], S Triglycerides: 504 mg/dl; S Cholesterol: 125 mg/dl; LDLc: 44mg/dl; HDLc: 21mg/dl. FP Glucose: 94. HbA1c: 6.1. TSH: 1.08. Ref Endocrinology Assessment: Acute Pancreatitis due to potential multiple mechanisms: (a) Hypertriglyceridemia, both genetic and drug [high dose estrogen, glucocorticoids] induced; (b) Direct pancreatotoxic effect of drugs [Estrogen, Prednisolone] Plan: Diet Rx, lipid lowering medicines [omega 3 fatty acids/ fibrates/ niacin/ statin] permanently. Possibility of “gentle” and safe ovulation induction, followed by surrogate pregnancy has been recommended in literature Discussion: Drug‐induced pancreatitis: Accounts for 0.1‐2% of AP. Potential mechanisms for drug‐induced AP include pancreatic duct constriction, cytotoxic and metabolic effects, accumulation of a toxic metabolite or intermediary, and hypersensitivity reactions; Negative effects of drugs, such as hypertriglyceridemia, chronic hypercalcemia, localized angioedema effect in the pancreas and arteriolar thrombosis [Culprit Drug Classes Ia, Ib, II, III, IV] Clomiphene induced severe hypertriglyceridemia and pancreatitis: Rarely reported in patients with baseline hypertriglyceridemia; mechanism similar to tamoxifen. Fenofibrate‐induced “nonlithogenic” recurrent pancreatitis: Single case reported with monotherapy [very few with simvastatin combination therapy]; mechanism unclear – related or unrelated to enhanced gall stone formation. In 7 fibrate trials with 40162 participants conducted over 5.3 years, 144 participants developed pancreatitis (84 assigned to fibrate therapy, 60 assigned to placebo) (RR, 1.39 [95% CI, 1.00‐1.95; P =.053; I2 = 0%]). However, in our case, we opine that Fenofibrate was a “saviour” than a “villain”
