DO  -  10.1002/jca.21385
AB  -  Purpose: Hypertriglyceridemia is the third leading cause of acute pancreatitis, responsible for 1‐4% of reported cases. Patients with severe or very severe hypertriglyceridemia (triglyceride level >1000 mg/dL) are at high risk of pancreatitis. The treatment of hypertriglyceridemic pancreatitis includes the conventional supportive care given in the setting of acute pancreatitis and management of serum triglycerides with an initial goal of <500 mg/dL. Suggested treatment modalities include therapeutic plasma exchange (TPE), insulin and heparin. No randomized trials have been conducted to compare the efficacy of TPE with insulin and/or heparin. The current ASFA guidelines assign a category III/grade 2C designation (optimum role of apheresis therapy not established/weak recommendation) to the use of TPE in hypertriglyceridemic pancreatitis. We report a case of hypertriglyceridemic necrotizing pancreatitis treated successfully with TPE. A 56‐year‐old man with no previous medical history presented with nausea, vomiting and mid‐epigastric abdominal pain for 4 days after excessive alcohol consumption. He also reported shortness of breath and cough for 6 hours prior to admission. The patient developed severe respiratory distress in the ED requiring emergent intubation. Admission laboratory tests included: triglycerides 2898 (<150) mg/dL, LDH 464 (100‐190) U/L, lipase 376 (22‐51) U/L, amylase 1324 (25‐110) U/L, glucose 1659 (65‐110) mg/dL, Cr 2.85 (0.4‐1.30) mg/dL, AST 25 (15‐40) u/L, calcium 7.2 (8.5‐10.5) mg/dL and Hgb 13.0 (13.5‐18) gm/dL. Subsequent CT scan showed severe necrotizing acute pancreatitis without biliary obstruction. Despite administration of both insulin and heparin, his condition continued to deteriorate. He developed renal failure (Cr 7.54 mg/dL) and anemia (Hgb 8.7 gm/dL) within 48 hours and his calcium decreased to 6.5 mg/dL despite supplementation. A single TPE of 1.1 plasma volumes (5.7 L) was performed 48 hours after admission using 5% albumin replacement along with calcium gluconate supplementation, 4 grams prior and 6 grams during the procedure. Methods: A case is reported with a literature review. Results: After one plasma exchange, the patient's triglyceride level dropped from 1856 to 442 (Figure) and remained less than 500 for his remaining hospitalization. On day 26, he was discharged in stable condition. Conclusions: One TPE dramatically lowered triglyceride levels and allowed full recovery in this patient with a potentially fatal case of necrotizing pancreatitis. TPE may be an effective primary treatment modality for hypertriglyceridemic pancreatitis. Pancreatitis related hypocalcemia may require aggressive calcium supplementation prior to and during TPE. (Figure Presented) .
