AB  -  INTERVENTION: Intervention1: Coconut oil massage: The preterm neonates will receive moderate pressure massage therapy using edible coconut oil (4 g/kg body weight). Oil massage will be done by mothers/trained staff nurses from day 3 of life till 28 days of life (COMPETE TRIAL – coconut oil massage in preterm neonates). During the massage the neonates will be nursed in an environment where the temperature will be maintained at 25 degree celsius, with minimal lighting and muted alarms to minimize exposure to stressful stimuli. The vital parameters (heart rate and oxygen saturation) will be continuously monitored throughout the procedure using a pulse oximeter. The standardized massage technique will be used for the study, i.e., it will begin by stroking from the top of the head down to the neck and then back up to the top of the head. Then it will be carried out from the neck, across the shoulders and back to the neck. Subsequently, it will be carried out from the upper back to the waist and then back up to the upper back followed by stroking from the thigh down to the foot and then back up to the thigh for both legs. Finally, it will end by stoking from the shoulder down to the hand and then back up to the shoulder for both arms. In each area the massage will comprise of 10 gentle strokes. The duration of each massage will be of 10 minutes and will be performed at 8‐hourly intervals, starting from morning, then afternoon and finally at night time for a duration of 4 weeks. Control Intervention1: Coconut oil application: The preterm neonates will receive topical application with edible coconut oil without any massage. The topical application will be done by mothers/trained staff nurses gently to minimize skin trauma or contamination. After proper handwashing, coconut oil (4 g/kg body CONDITION: Health Condition 1: P073‐ Preterm [premature] newborn [other] PRIMARY OUTCOME: Weight gain velocity (g/kg/day)Timepoint: At the time of enrolment (baseline) and then weight gain in g/kg/day at 4 weeks INCLUSION CRITERIA: Medically stable preterm neonates between 28+0 weeks and 32+6 weeks gestation will be enrolled at 72 hours of birth. SECONDARY OUTCOME: Head circumference gain velocity (cm/week)Timepoint: At the time of enrollment and weekly till 4 weeks Insulin like growth factor (IGF‐1) levelsTimepoint: After 4 weeks of intervention Intraventricular hemorrhage (grade 2 or more)Timepoint: At the time of enrollment and after 4 weeks of intervention Length gain velocity (cm/week)Timepoint: At the time of enrollment and weekly till 4 weeks Neonatal mortalityTimepoint: At 4 weeks of age Parathyroid hormone (PTH) levelsTimepoint: After 4 weeks of intervention Proven/probable sepsisTimepoint: At the time of enrollment and during hospital stay Salivary cortisol levelsTimepoint: After 4 weeks of intervention Serum calcium, phosphorus, alkaline phosphatase and triglycerides levelsTimepoint: At the time of enrollment and after 4 weeks of intervention Total serum bilirubin (peak value)Timepoint: During routine clinical care till 4 weeks of intervention Urinary creatinine & phosphorus and Tubular reabsorption of phosphate (TRP)Timepoint: After 4 weeks of intervention Vitamin D levelsTimepoint: After 4 weeks of intervention
