AB  -  Introduction and Aims: Current therapies for the treatment of hyperphosphatemia are frequently insufficient to achieve the recommended K/DOQI goal of maintaining serum phosphorus level at 3.5‐5.5 mg/dl.We aimed to evaluate the safety and the efficacy of niacinamide as an adjunctive therapy to calcium carbonate in hemodialysis patients. Methods: Sixty hemodialysis patients with serum phosphorus level > 5.0 mg/dl were randomly assigned to 8 weeks of the study. Patients were divided into two groups: group I: 30 cases received calcium carbonate only and group II:30 cases received a combination of calcium carbonate and nicotinamide. Nicotinamide dose was started as500mg/day and increased on 8th day to 1000mg/day. Results: In group II: serum phosphorus level fell significantly (P<0.001), calcium×phosphorus product dropped significantly (P<0.001) together with a significant elevation of serum calcium (P<0.05). In groupI: there was insignificant change in former parameters (all P values>0.05). Intact parathyroid hormone, uric acid, platelet count, total cholesterol, hemoglobin, AST, ALT and lipid profile remained insignificantly changed in both groups. Diarrhea, flushing and skin rash were the major adverse effects seen with nicotinamide therapy resulting in early withdrawal of 4 patients from the study. Conclusions: In hemodialysis patients, nicotinamide in a low dose of 1000 mg daily can effectively reduce serum phosphorus level when administered with calcium carbonate (as phosphate binder) with mild potential side effects reported.
